                  <h2>Wing-Huen Ip</h2>
                  <p>Professor Wing-Huen Ip has made significant contributions to deep-space exploration, including comets and Outer Planets. In particular, his contribution to the CASSINI-Huygens mission was recognised as pioneering and non-replaceable. He is also a pioneer in the study of the interrelation of planetesimals with Uranus and Neptune in the early solar system and in satellite-ring-magnetosphere interaction.</p>
                  <p>Due to his significant achievements in planetary science and related missions, Professor Ip is a most worthy awardee of the 2020 CAS/COSPAR Jeoujang JAW Award.</p>

                	<h3>Biography</h3>
                  <p>Prof. Wing-Huen Ip received his PhD degree from UCSD in 1974 to be followed by working as postdoc researcher at the same school before moving to the Max-Planck-Instutut fur Aeronomie (now MPI fur Sonnensystemforschung) as staff scientist in 1978. He participated in several planetary exploration missions of ESA and NASA including Giotto, Deep Space 1, Galileo, Cassini-Huygen, and Rosetta. The joint NASA-ESA Cassini-Huygens mission was originally proposed as Project Cassini to ESA by Daniel Gautier of the Observatoire Meudon and Wing Ip in 1982.  After returning to Taiwan in 1998 permanently, Prof. Ip had served as Dean of Science and Vice President of National Central University besides his teaching and research activity at the Institute of Astronomy. He is currently leading a research project on science education inTaiwan. He co-founded the Asia-Oceania Geosciences Society together with Prof. Ian Axford and Prof. Yosuke Kamide in 2003, and is currently Chair of its Regional Advisory Committee to promote regional cooperation. He is Academician of Academia Sinica, AGU Fellow, IAA Member, and received several awards including NASA’s Exceptional Public Service Medal (2009), Axford Medal of AOGS (2011), and the Kuiper Prize of AAS/DPS (2020).</p>
