                	<h3>Biography</h3>
                  <p>Takanori Nishiyama was born and raised in Hokkaido, Japan. In 2004, he enrolled at Tohoku University, Sendai, Japan. He earned his bachelor’s degree in physics in 2008 and Doctor of Science in 2013. His thesis focused on coupling processes between the magnetosphere and the lower thermosphere/ionosphere via novel optical observations and data analysis. Using the REIMEI satellite and a ground-based EMCCD camera, he investigated the generation mechanisms and temporal/spatial characteristics of pulsating auroras. In 2013, he joined the National Institute of Polar Research, Japan. Since then his research interests have broadened to include coupling between the magnetosphere and the mesosphere/lower thermosphere. Using the Program of the Antarctic Syowa mesosphere-stratosphere-troposphere/incoherent scatter (PANSY) radar, he investigated polar mesospheric winter echo (PMWE) to elucidate its mechanism that is expected to closely relate to energetic particle precipitations through the magnetosphere. He visited Syowa station (69.0°S, 39.6°E) in the Antarctic twice as part of Japanese Antarctic Research Expedition (JARE). For 14 months (November 2017 - January 2019), he served as a wintering scientist at Syowa station, where he led novel resonance scattering lidar observations. </p>
