                	<h3>Biography</h3>
                  <p>Daniel began research at the University of Sydney, Australia. He worked on his PhD from 2009 to 2012. The title of his doctoral thesis was "Electromagnetic Strong Turbulence and Nonlinear Processes in the Solar Wind" (supervised by Prof. Iver H. Cairns). This work focused on numerical modelling of nonlinear processes associated with high-frequency Langmuir waves, and on observations of these waves by the two STEREO spacecraft in the solar wind.</p>
                  <p>In 2012 Daniel started a Postdoctoral fellowship at the Swedish Institute of Space Physics (IRF) in Uppsala, Sweden. This researched focused on magnetic reconnection at Earth's magnetopause, using data from the four Cluster spacecraft. Since 2016 Daniel has remained a researcher at IRF and started with the Magnetospheric Multiscale (MMS) mission. He continues his research on topics such as electron transport and heating in magnetic reconnection, the role of waves in magnetic reconnection, and the properties of waves and nonlinear structures at the magnetopause and in the solar wind. Daniel is also involved in the calibration of electric field measurements onboard the MMS and Solar Orbiter missions.</p>
