                	<h3>Biography</h3>
                  <p>Giorgio Baiocco has been active in research in biological effects of ionizing radiation since 2013, after a PhD and a first post-doc in the field of fundamental nuclear physics. During his work at the Physics Department, University of Pavia, Italy, where he currently holds a position as senior researcher, he has been studying the effects of space radiation on human health – a major limiting factor for manned deep-space exploration. Recently, he has been the PI of the PERSEO (PErsonal Radiation Shielding for intErplanetary missiOns) project, selected and funded by the Italian Space Agency. The project has led to the realization and successful test on board the International Space Station of the first prototype of a water-filled garment for use in a pressurized space habitat for personal protection of astronauts against solar particle events. In addition to studying innovating solutions for radiation shielding, among other topics of relevance he has been working on the effects of neutrons (generated by space radiation interacting with spacecraft walls or planetary atmosphere) and effects of space radiation on visual system activation. He has authored several publications in the field and carries out continuous teaching and dissemination activities about space radiation research.</p>
