                  <p>Katharina received her BSc degree in Chemistry from the University of Bielefeld, Germany,  and her MSc degree in Chemistry for Renewable Energy from Uppsala University, Sweden. She carried out her degree project at the Center for Bioenergy and Photosynthesis, Arizona State University, USA. Katharina obtained her PhD from Imperial College London in 2015, where she worked with Prof Bill Rutherford on nature’s water splitting enzyme, Photosystem II. Consecutively, Katharina received a Research Fellowship from the European Space Agency (ESTEC/Noordwijk, the Netherlands) for an independent research project on solar hydrogen production in microgravity environment. Following her work at ESA, Katharina received a Leopoldina Postdoctoral Scholarship to work with Prof. Harry B. Gray at the California Institute of Technology, where she developed new electrocatalytic materials for electrochemical ammonia production.</p>
