                  <p>Vitali Müller studied physics at the Leibniz University of Hanover, Germany, where he heard in his undergraduate courses for the first time about laser interferometers to measure distances changes, for instance, to detect gravitational waves with the LISA satellite mission.</p>
                  <p>At the Max-Planck-Institute for Gravitational Physics in Hannover, which focuses on the development of such interferometers for ground- and space-based detectors, he found his scientific home base. Vitali completed at the institute his bachelor, master and PhD thesis (2018, “Design Considerations for Future Geodesy Missions and for Space Laser Interferometry”), which all were related to optics, interferometry and gravimetry, mainly in the context of the GRACE Follow-On mission. This US-German satellite pair was launched in 2018 to map Earth’s gravity field, and is equipped with the first laser ranging interferometer (LRI) acting as technology demonstrator.</p>
